<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from EEF – the manufacturers’ organisation (LTD0010)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:3pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Written evidence from EEF – the manufacturers’ organisation (LTD0010)</span></p><p style="margin:3pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#ce007c; font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:3pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#ce007c; font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">About EEF</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">EEF is the representative voice of manufacturing, engineering and technology-based businesses with a membership of over 2,000 companies covering approximately 6,000 sites. A large part of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">our</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> representational work focuses on the issues that make a differen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ce to the productivity and competitiveness of UK manufacturing including investment, innovation, and tax issues. In this submission we set out EEF’s view on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the challenges behind the existing structures for local decision making around transport, with part</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">icular reference to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the maintenance of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> local roads</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:3pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#ce007c; font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">EEF believes that the current </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">structure for managing local roads is not the most effective way to deliver value for money</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. This is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a key issue given declining </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">central government funding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">authorities. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Given this, it is important to foster collaboration and long term planning as crucial elements of local decision making on transport. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Local Transport Bodies represent an opportunity to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">do just that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The comments we have made bel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ow outline our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">view on a subset of the committee’s questions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, we intend to study this area further with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">more detailed work in 2014.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:3pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#ce007c; font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Some advantages from devolving decision making</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is significant reform underway to transform the Highways Agency to provide funding cer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tainty</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> along with a structured plan of projects across set five year</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> period</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Similar structural challenges exist at the local level which cou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ld benefit from similar reforms. H</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">owever </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">local authority</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> roads are classified and managed separately </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">despite 84% o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f locally managed roads being A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">roads and the local road network being valued at around £400bn.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">From an industry point of view</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the distinction between the Highways Agency and loca</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lly managed roads is arbitrary. Businesses</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> need</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">well maintained roads and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the right connections, particularly to ports, to allow reliable journeys and consequently efficient business operation.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are some a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dvantages to devolving decision-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">making to the local level, in particular allowing a more responsive approach to developi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ng transport projects based on local business and public needs. However, the benefits may be outweighed by the inefficient structures</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and annual budgeting approach which exists</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (highlighted below).</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The challenge that exists at the local level is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a decision</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on how to manage maintenance and congestion. Our</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> analysis of the main </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">barriers to effective delivery in these areas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> highlights the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">decision making process</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as a key barrier to improving the local road network and the Transport Select Committee is right to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">look at this.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:3pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#ce007c; font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Value for Money and asset management</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Taking local road maintenance as an example</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> poor value for money is a particular challenge with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">funding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> not being put to its most efficient use. The Audit Commission highlighted in a report that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> despite </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a 73% increase in cash spending across 2000/01 to 2009/10</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> there was no real increase in purchasing power as a result of high inflation in the road c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">onstruction sector, additionally only 40% of local highway authorities benchmarked their road maintenance p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rices and regularly evaluate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> contracts.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Alongside this, achieving value for money is undermined by an annual local authority budget cycle, leading to an annual approach to road project development </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">associated</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> costly procurement and low levels of c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ollaboration between local h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ighway authorities. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he opportunities for reductions in procurement s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pend are minimised</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as a result of this annual cycle</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Without longer-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">term contracts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the supply chain also underinvests in the required skills and capital machi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nery</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, a problem exacerbated by the declining expenditure on local road maintenance.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is also a loose requirement for the development and use of asset management </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">plans;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as a result the state of the asset (local roads) is unclear</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> leading to unexpecte</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d asset fail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ure following severe weather. This then leads to a more costly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reactive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> maintenance approach</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> which is estimated to be at least 20 times as expensive as resurfacing per square metre</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reactive </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">approach </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">accounts for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">between 14 to 50% of loca</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">l authority</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> road maintenance budgets</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">). Additionally </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a greater proportion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of budgets will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">subsequently be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> used for insurance claims for damage from road users.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:3pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#ce007c; font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Local Transport Bodies and collaboration</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Local Transport Bodies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (LTBs)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> are a possible way of rationalising the over 150 local highway authorities down to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">less than</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 40, to allow greater cross border collaboration and longer contract lengths. Collaboration is important given the spatial dimension of transport and the interconn</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ected nature of journeys taken on separa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tely managed stretches of road.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">LTBs are a good model to build on and encouragingly many local authorities are coming together along LEP/LTB boundaries as combined authorities to tackle</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, among other things, transport</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> – most notably the North East, Sheffield City Region and Liverpool City Region LEPs.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Government should be encouraged to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">build on their current Highways Agency reforms by looking at local decision making structures for transport. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">LTBs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> would be a good p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lace to start to seek greater collaboration, effective asset management strategies and longer term investment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> plans. These areas are crucial for delivering a world class local road network.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:3pt 0pt 6pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:3pt 0pt 6pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:3pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:right"><span style="color:#ce007c; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:3pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="color:#808080; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> Managing a valuable asset: improving local road conditions, APPG Highway Maintenance, October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:3pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="color:#808080; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> Going the Distance, Audit Commission, May 2011</span></p><p style="margin:3pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="color:#808080; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> Infrastructure Cost Review: Main Report, Infrastructure UK, December 2010</span></p><p style="margin:3pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="color:#808080; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> Department for Transport Road</span><span style="color:#808080; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> Condition Statistics, Table RDC0310, February 2013</span></p><p style="margin:3pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="color:#808080; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> Managing a valuable asset, October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:3pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="color:#808080; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt"> Going the Distance, May 2011</span></p></body></html>